narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: Adobe Photoshop and Bridge skills, basic camera usage, printing on the inkjet photo printers, knowledge regarding other famous photographers.

I learned how to be a better photographer, and more about the active art of photography, as well as some of the systems and mechanics of the way cameras work and a lot about different artists and the history of photography.
This class was so amazing. Ted is such a great professor, and really took the time to explain to us how to treat our photography with more intentionality, and elevate it using adobe software.
Fundamentals of using a camera and photo editing in photoshop/bridge, exploring your voice as a photographer, exposure to the work of various well-known photographers with different stules/methods.
I loved this course. You learn a little bit of everything - a little bit of photoshop, and really just learning to get in touch with your creative side.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: ample work time and one-on-one help with the professor 
Weaknesses: does not necessarily challenge anyone too work outside their comfort zone or very many structured lessons/check-in assignments

Ted and my TF were the real strengths of this course, as well as so much creative freedom which really helped me find my voice as an artist. The class can be a little bit disorganized, but in the end, the professors are very forgiving and the course is excellent in general.
I loved our trips to the art gallery and to see MFA student portfolio work. It was great to gain inspiration in this way. I would 100% incorporate for of this into the class.

Strengths: good intro course, did not require prior knowledge of photography to be able to engage fully. Ted and Whitney were very involved, gave frequent and personal feedback which was really helpful.  

Don't really have any suggestions for improvement!
Strengths: you are able to create a lot of meaningful work and grow in your photography skills throughout the semester.
I loved this course, nothing to be improved

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes because if you manage your time wisely, there is not a lot of homework besides taking some photos since you do all of the editing and printing in class. A good basic intro to photography but may not be needed if have any prior experience.

I would highly recommend this course to another student. It is a great course, and I looked forward to coming to class and felt like it was a great way to engage with art, photography, and storytelling.

Yes! It's unlike any other classes I've taken at Yale, due to the hands-on nature of the course. I learned a lot, got a creative outlet, and overall deepened my appreciation for photography as an art form.
Yes! This course is great for anyone who is willing to spend the time to take their photography to the next level.
Yes! If you're looking for a class that will give you the time and motivation to devote effort to something creative at Yale, totally
